{"id":"1503.08099","submitter":"Shugo Yasuda","authors":"Shugo Yasuda","title":"A Monte Carlo simulation for kinetic chemotaxis models: an application\n  to the traveling population wave","comments":null,"journal-ref":"Journal of Computational Physics 330, 1022-1042 (2017)","doi":"10.1016/j.jcp.2016.10.066","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.bio-ph q-bio.CB","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  A Monte Carlo simulation of chemotactic bacteria is developed on the basis of\nthe kinetic model and is applied to a one-dimensional traveling population wave\nin a microchannel. In this simulation, the Monte Carlo method, which calculates\nthe run-and-tumble motions of bacteria, is coupled with a finite volume method\nto calculate the macroscopic transport of the chemical cues in the environment.\nThe simulation method can successfully reproduce the traveling population wave\nof bacteria that was observed experimentally and reveal the microscopic\ndynamics of bacterium coupled with the macroscopic transports of the chemical\ncues and bacteria population density. The results obtained by the Monte Carlo\nmethod are also compared with the asymptotic solution derived from the kinetic\nchemotaxis equation in the continuum limit, where the Knudsen number, which is\ndefined by the ratio of the mean free path of bacterium to the characteristic\nlength of the system, vanishes. The validity of the Monte Carlo method in the\nasymptotic behaviors for small Knudsen numbers is numerically verified.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 25 Mar 2015 08:27:48 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 31 Mar 2015 09:00:08 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Sun, 8 Jan 2017 20:23:48 GMT"}],"update_date":"2017-01-10"}
{"id":"1504.02377","submitter":"Florian Kuhnel","authors":"Florian Kuhnel and Marit Sandstad","title":"Corpuscular Consideration of Eternal Inflation","comments":"10 pages, 2 figures; revised version to match submitted version","journal-ref":"Eur.Phys.J. C75 (2015) 10, 505","doi":"10.1140/epjc/s10052-015-3736-7","report-no":null,"categories":"gr-qc astro-ph.CO hep-th","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We review the paradigm of eternal inflation in the light of the recently\nproposed corpuscular picture of space-time. Comparing the strength of the\naverage fluctuation of the field up its potential with that of quantum\ndepletion, we show that the latter can be dominant. We then study the full\nrespective distributions in order to show that the fraction of the space-time\nwhich has an increasing potential is always below the eternal-inflation\nthreshold. We prove that for monomial potentials eternal inflaton is excluded.\nThis is likely to hold for other models as well.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 25 Mar 2015 10:35:01 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 29 May 2015 07:49:56 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Thu, 13 Aug 2015 09:27:54 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-11-16"}
{"id":"1505.05055","submitter":"Carsten Burstedde","authors":"Carsten Burstedde and Johannes Holke and Tobin Isaac","title":"Bounds on the number of discontinuities of Morton-type space-filling\n  curves","comments":"25 pages, 16 figures, 2 tables: added proofs for triangles and\n  tetrahedra; moved appendices into main document","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cs.CG","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The Morton- or z-curve is one example for a space filling curve: Given a\nlevel of refinement L, it maps the interval [0, 2**dL) one-to-one to a set of\nd-dimensional cubes of edge length 2**-L that form a subdivision of the unit\ncube. Similar curves have been proposed for triangular and tetrahedral unit\ndomains. In contrast to the Hilbert curve that is continuous, the Morton-type\ncurves produce jumps.\n  We prove that any contiguous subinterval of the curve divides the domain into\na bounded number of face-connected subdomains. For the hypercube case and\narbitrary dimension, the subdomains are star-shaped and the bound is indeed\ntwo. For the simplicial case in dimensions 2 and 3, the bound is proportional\nto the depth of refinement L. We supplement the paper with theoretical and\ncomputational studies on the frequency of jumps for a quantitative assessment.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 24 Mar 2015 22:25:50 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 20 May 2015 20:05:03 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Sat, 1 Aug 2015 17:59:50 GMT"},{"version":"v4","created":"Thu, 20 Apr 2017 08:05:35 GMT"}],"update_date":"2017-04-21"}
